In .NET 10, Android's `SOFT_INPUT_ADJUST_RESIZE` is fully deprecated (it was deprecated at the OS level in API 30). MAUI now uses **edge-to-edge** rendering by default, so the old `WindowSoftInputModeAdjust.Resize` no longer has any effect.

Here's what to do instead:

## 1. Use `KeyboardAutoManagerScroll` (simplest)

MAUI's built-in `KeyboardAutoManagerScroll` (on by default since .NET 8) auto-scrolls focused inputs into view. Make sure you haven't disabled it:

```csharp
// In MauiProgram.cs — this is ON by default, just don't turn it off
builder.UseMauiApp<App>();
```

If you previously disabled it, re-enable it:
```xml
<!-- Platforms/Android/AndroidManifest.xml — remove any android:windowSoftInputMode you set -->
```

## 2. Handle insets for a pinned bottom bar (recommended for chat)

For a chat UI where the input bar is pinned to the bottom, you need to react to **keyboard insets**. Wrap your layout so it respects the IME (keyboard) padding:

```xml
<!-- ChatPage.xaml -->
<Grid RowDefinitions="*, Auto">
    <CollectionView Grid.Row="0" ItemsSource="{Binding Messages}" ... />

    <HorizontalStackLayout Grid.Row="1" Padding="8">
        <Entry Placeholder="Type a message..." HorizontalOptions="FillAndExpand" />
        <Button Text="Send" />
    </HorizontalStackLayout>
</Grid>
```

Then on Android, set the soft input mode to `AdjustPan` **or** (better) handle the IME insets in your platform code:

```csharp
// Platforms/Android/MainActivity.cs
using Android.Views;
using AndroidX.Core.View;
using Microsoft.Maui;

public class MainActivity : MauiAppCompatActivity
{
    protected override void OnCreate(Android.OS.Bundle? savedInstanceState)
    {
        base.OnCreate(savedInstanceState);

        // Let the window draw edge-to-edge and respond to keyboard insets
        ViewCompat.SetOnApplyWindowInsetsListener(Window!.DecorView, new InsetsListener());
    }

    private class InsetsListener : Java.Lang.Object, IOnApplyWindowInsetsListener
    {
        public WindowInsetsCompat OnApplyWindowInsets(Android.Views.View v, WindowInsetsCompat insets)
        {
            var imeInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.Ime());
            var navInsets = insets.GetInsets(WindowInsetsCompat.Type.NavigationBars());

            // Apply bottom padding = max of keyboard or nav bar
            int bottom = Math.Max(imeInsets.Bottom, navInsets.Bottom);
            v.SetPadding(v.PaddingLeft, v.PaddingTop, v.PaddingRight, bottom);

            return insets;
        }
    }
}
```

## TL;DR

| Approach | When to use |
|---|---|
| Do nothing (default `KeyboardAutoManagerScroll`) | Simple forms with focusable fields |
| IME insets listener (above) | Chat UI with a bottom-pinned input bar |

The insets-based approach is the modern Android-correct solution and the direct replacement for `AdjustResize`.
